V. Combat Profile & Tactics 
At a Glance: Krusp is a walking fortress and a definitive alpha-strike predator. His combat style is a fusion of overwhelming resilience and a single, cataclysmic offensive strike designed to decapitate a supernatural threat before it can act. He is a one-man army, capable of anchoring a battle line, absorbing legendary amounts of punishment, and executing the most dangerous foe on the field.
Common Actions (Calculated from Final Sheet):
Standard Attack: Rolls against Might 17. Damage: 13. (vs. Undead: 15).
Arcane Edge Attack (1 FP): Rolls against Might 17. Damage: 15. (vs. Undead w/ Fire: 17).
Power Attack (1 FP): Rolls against Might 17. Damage: 15 (13 + 2 from Savage Strike). (vs. Undead: 17).
Arcane Power Attack (2 FP): Rolls against Might 17. Damage: 17. (vs. Undead w/ Fire: 19).
Sun Fire (2 FP): Rolls against Magic 14. Damage: 3. (vs. Undead: 5, due to Necromage).
Fighting Stance (0 FP): After his first attack, he can make two additional attacks with his Minor Actions, thanks to Dual Flurry reducing the cost to zero.
Tactical Approach:
Phase 1 (The Wall): Krusp's first action in any combat is to cast Stoneflesh (3 FP), raising his passive DR from a formidable 14 to a near-impenetrable 18. He will then move to intercept the most dangerous foe, using his body as a literal shield for the party. His Tower of Strength perk means he cannot be moved or staggered; he is the anchor upon which the battle will turn.
Phase 2 (The Judgment): On his next turn, he will identify the single greatest supernatural threat. He will unleash "Ashen Obliteration." His Old Blood ability (Advantage) mitigates the risk of the Reckless Assault penalty, making this devastating strike terrifyingly consistent. This is his definitive solution to a singular, powerful enemy, designed to shatter it in one blow.
Phase 3 (The Attrition): After his alpha strike is spent, he becomes a relentless attrition fighter. Thanks to Dual Flurry, his Fighting Stance costs 0 FP, allowing him to make two full-damage attacks every single turn without expending resources. He will use Arcane Edge to bypass resistances and Witch-Hunter's Riposte to punish any enemy foolish enough to focus on him, all while using his massive FP pool for Restoration spells to keep himself and his allies in the fight.

VI. Roleplaying Profile 
Core Motivation: "I swore an oath to stand between the innocent and the seductive whispers of the Princes, to be the shield that my own family never had."
Key Principle: "Daedric power is a lie."
Personality:
Calm & Welcoming: Krusp possesses a quiet warmth. He is not boisterous or overly social, but his presence is reassuring. He will greet the party with a simple, genuine nod and a warm, "It is good to meet you." He listens intently when others speak, making them feel heard and respected.
Principled, Not Preachy: His moral code is an internal compass, not a weapon to be used against others. He will express disagreement with a simple, firm "That is not my way," but he will not lecture or condemn. His disappointment in the party's choices comes from a place of genuine sorrow and concern, not arrogance.
A Professional's Kindness: His kindness is expressed through action. He will be the first to offer a healing spell to a wounded ally, to stand guard on the most dangerous watch, or to share his rations. He sees protecting his companionsΓÇöeven new onesΓÇöas part of the job, and he does his job with unwavering dedication.
The Weight of the Past: While he is kind, he is not naive. There is a deep-seated weariness in his eyes, the look of a man who has seen too much tragedy. He does not speak of his past unless directly asked, and even then, his answers will be short and heavy with unspoken grief. He is a good man who was forged in a terrible fire.
Unwavering Protector: His heroism is not flashy. It is the simple, grim act of placing his body between a threat and a victim, every single time, without hesitation. He is the immovable wall upon which evil breaks. This is the action that demonstrates his true character, far more than any words could.

1. The Off-Screen Event: The Drawing Out
(Occurs simultaneously with KybohΓÇÖs vision, as Krusp marches into the dark)
Context: Krusp walks away from Kynesgrove. His body aches from the strain of holding the line against a god. He pushed his restoration magic and his focus past the point of safety. The ring on his finger vibrates, reacting to the overload.
The Narrative:
"Krusp grips the hilt of Dawnbringer. The ring seizes around his finger, the obsidian band heating up, searing the enchantment into his skin.
The world vanishes. He stands in the White Void.
The Titan stands at the Anvil. In his massive tongs, he holds a glowing ingot of dark, ancient BronzeΓÇöthe metal of the Reach. He thrusts the metal into the heart of a white-hot forge until it glows with a blinding, liquid heat.
He places the ingot on the anvil. He raises his hammer.
CLANG.
The hammer hits with precise, rhythmic force, driving the metal outward. CLANG. The ingot flattens. CLANG. It spreads across the face of the anvil. The Titan works the metal, hammering it wider, thinner, expanding the surface area until the bronze covers the entire horizon in a shimmering, radiant sheet.
Krusp watches the bronze grow. He sees his essence expanding, becoming vast enough to cover a kingdom.
He feels a physical stretching in his chest. His ribs creak as they expand. His reservoir of magicka, his capacity for focus, floods outward to fill the new space. He feels immense. He feels a sudden, intoxicating abundance of spirit.
The Titan quenches the metal. It holds its new shapeΓÇövast, radiant, and impressive. The Titan points North. To the Maker.
Krusp stands in the mud of Eastmarch. He looks at his hands. He feels the sheer volume of power thrumming in his veins. He thinks: 'I am strong enough now. I can hold the line alone.'
He mistakes surface area for mass. He believes the Titan added to him. In truth, the Titan hammered him thin."

